Test parameters for clustering of amphioxus data

Arun Chavan

Started: 2020-12-11
Last edited: 2021-03-11 20:49:37

1 Background

Here we

  1. Read QC filtered data
  2. Perform normalization (CPT and sctransform) and clustering (Louvain and Leiden)
  3. Assess clustering based on number of marker genes and other metrics, and re-assess QC filtration criteria

3 Data

bflo <- readRDS(here(basedir, "data/04_qc/bflo_seurat_qc-filtered.rds"))

3.1 Read saved objects if starting over

The clustering steps, merging of cluster, and finding markers takes a while. Running all combinations below can take about 5 hours. I have saved to disk the resulting seurat objects and csv files with markers. If starting over, read these files instead of rerunning all analyses, and skip to the UMAPs section below.

4 Gene info

gene.info <- read_tsv(here(genomedir, "gene-info/gene-info_from-gtf.tsv"))

# extract gene lists (replace _ with - for compatibility with how Seurat stores gene names)
genes.rrna <- gene.info %>% filter(gbkey == "rRNA")                       %>% .$gene_id %>% unique() %>% gsub(pattern = "_", replacement = "-") 
genes.mt   <- gene.info %>% filter(seqname == "NC_000834.1")              %>% .$gene_id %>% unique() %>% gsub(pattern = "_", replacement = "-")
genes.good <- gene.info %>% filter(!gene_id %in% c(genes.rrna, genes.mt)) %>% .$gene_id %>% unique() %>% gsub(pattern = "_", replacement = "-")

Note: two genes are both mitochondrial and rRNA genes, thus percent reads will not add to 100%

5 Analyses with different combinations of gene sets, normalization methods, clustering algorithms

5.1 All genes

5.1.1 CPT normalization

Standard normalization in Seurat: CPT (CPT = Counts per 10k) followed by log transformation.

bf_all <- NormalizeData(bflo, verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  FindVariableFeatures(selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000, verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  ScaleData(verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  RunPCA(npcs = 200, verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  FindNeighbors(dims = 1:200, k.param = 20, nn.method = "annoy", annoy.metric = "cosine") %>% 
  RunUMAP(dims = 1:200, min.dist = 0.1, umap.method = "umap-learn", metric = "cosine",
          reduction.name = "umap.cpt", reduction.key = "umapCPT_", verbose = FALSE)
Computing nearest neighbor graph
Computing SNN

5.1.2 SCT normalization

Perform SCT normalization:

bf_all <- SCTransform(bf_all, vars.to.regress = "percent.mt",
                      conserve.memory = T, verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  RunPCA(assay = "SCT", npcs = 200, 
         reduction.name = "pca.sct", reduction.key = "pcaSCT_", verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  FindNeighbors(dims = 1:200, reduction = "pca.sct", 
                k.param = 20, nn.method = "annoy", 
                annoy.metric = "cosine", verbose = FALSE) %>% 
  RunUMAP(reduction = "pca.sct", dims = 1:200, min.dist = 0.1, 
          umap.method = "umap-learn", metric = "cosine", 
          reduction.name = "umap.sct", reduction.key = "umapSCT_", verbose = FALSE)

plot_umap <- function(genes, norm.method, clust.method) {
  object <- get(glue("bf_{genes}"))
  object <- SetIdent(object, value = glue("{genes}_{norm.method}_{clust.method}_res10_merged"))
  p <- DimPlot(object, reduction = glue("umap.{norm.method}"), label = TRUE, repel = TRUE) +
    labs(subtitle = glue("{genes} genes, {norm.method}, {clust.method}")) +
    theme_half_open_nogrid() +
    theme(aspect.ratio = 1)
  
  ggsave(here(basedir, glue("results/05a_clustering_test-parameters/plots/umap_{genes}genes_{norm.method}_{clust.method}.pdf")), plot = p, device = cairo_pdf, width = 5.5, height = 4.5, units = "in")
  
  print(p)
}

    }
  }
}

7 Distribution of number of cells

plot_n_cells_density <- function(genes, norm.method, clust.method) {
  dat <- get(glue("bf_{genes}"))@meta.data %>% 
    group_by(!!sym(glue("{genes}_{norm.method}_{clust.method}_res10_merged"))) %>% 
    tally() %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    rename(cluster = !!sym(glue("{genes}_{norm.method}_{clust.method}_res10_merged")),
           n_cells = n)
  
  ggplot(dat, aes(x = n_cells)) +
    geom_density(fill = "grey") +
    labs(subtitle = glue("{genes} genes, {norm.method}, {clust.method}")) +
    annotation_custom(grid::textGrob(
      x = unit(0.6, "npc"), 
      y = unit(0.8, "npc"), 
      label = c(glue("min = {min(dat$n_cells)}\\\n
           median = {median(dat$n_cells)}\\\n
           max = {max(dat$n_cells)}")), 
      gp = grid::gpar(fontfamily = .use_font, cex = 0.75),
      hjust = 0
    )) +
    theme_half_open_grid()
}
n_cell_density <- list()

for (genes in c("all", "good")) {
  for (norm.method in c("cpt", "sct")) {
    for (clust.method in c("louvain", "leiden")) {
      n_cell_density[[genes]][[norm.method]][[clust.method]] <- plot_n_cells_density(
        genes = genes,
        norm.method = norm.method,
        clust.method = clust.method
      )
    }
  }
}

find_all_markers <- function(genes = c("all", "good"), 
                             norm.method = c("cpt", "sct"),

                             suffix = "res10_merged") {

8.3 Number of markers vs number of genes

plot_markers_vs_genes <- function(genes, norm.method, clust.method) {
  object <- get(glue("bf_{genes}"))
  
  genes.median <- object@meta.data %>% 
    group_by(!!sym(glue("{genes}_{norm.method}_{clust.method}_res10_merged"))) %>% 
    summarize(genes_median = median(nFeature_RNA),
              n_cells = n()) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    rename(cluster = !!sym(glue("{genes}_{norm.method}_{clust.method}_res10_merged"))) %>% 
    mutate(cluster = as.numeric(cluster))
  
  n_markers <- markers[[genes]][[norm.method]][[clust.method]] %>% 
    group_by(cluster) %>% 
    tally() %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    mutate(cluster = as.numeric(cluster))
  
  dat <- inner_join(genes.median, n_markers, by = "cluster")
  
  ggplot(dat, aes(x = genes_median, y = n, label = cluster, fill = n_cells)) +
    geom_point(shape = 21, size = 2, color = "black") +
    scale_fill_binned(type = "viridis", #low = "#fee6ce", high = "#e6550d", 
                      trans = "sqrt",  
                      breaks = seq(0, 1750, 250), 
                      limits = c(0, 1750)) +
    coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, NA)) +
    labs(y = "n_markers",
         x = "n_genes (median)",
         subtitle = glue("{genes} genes, {norm.method}, {clust.method}")) +
    theme_half_open_grid() +
    theme(aspect.ratio = 1,
          legend.key.height = unit(2, "char"))

}
markers_vs_genes <- list()
for (genes in c("all", "good")) {
  for (norm.method in c("cpt", "sct")) {
    for (clust.method  in c("louvain", "leiden")) {
      markers_vs_genes[[genes]][[norm.method]][[clust.method]] <- plot_markers_vs_genes(
        genes = genes, 
        norm.method = norm.method, 
        clust.method = clust.method
      )
    }
  }
}

10 Notes

  1. It looks like both Louvain and Leiden clustering result in more number of clusters with SCT normalization than with CPT normalization.
    • Here we used resolution = 10 for clustering, which resulted in more than 70-75 cluster, and upon merging small and similar clusters, we get about 35-45 clusters.
    • I didn’t save the results, but I also tried running these with resolution = 1, 2, and 5, all of which, upon merging small and similar clusters resulted in approximately similar number of final clusters.
    • This numner of clusters aligns also with old analyses, where for each of the 3 tissues, there were about 10-12 clusters. Here we are clustering all tissue together.
  2. All combinations of parameters result in clusters of similar sizes, where the median size of clusters is about 120 cells.
  3. There is some variation in the number of markers genes per cluster based on the parameters, but not a lot.
    • All clusters have at least about 90 marker genes. This is in contrast to the old analyses (with the genbank genome), where there were quite a few clusters that didn’t have any markers.
    • This is with Bonferroni correction, so the actual number is likely higher. When actually performing marker gene detection, we will use BH correction.
    • One of the criteria we set out with for detemining whether the clusters were “real” was that they should have a certain number of marker genes, unlike the old analyses. In the old analyses the total number of genes detected per cell were also lower, and thus those clusters without any markers were likely made of cells with very low UMIs. Even though they might have been from real cells, without enough number of UMIs, we couldn’t extract any meaningful information from them. Here we seem to have overcome that problem at least partially.
  4. Unsurprisingly, the number of marker genes detected for each cluster is directly proportinal to the median number of genes detected per cell for that cluster. The cluster that break away from this pattern are the clusters that have a lot of cells. These clusters tend to have more marker genes than you would expect based on the number of genes detected in their cells.
  5. Since there aren’t huge differences in the numner of markers and clustering between these parameters, we will go with SCT for normalization since it’s generally better than CPT (see notes on SCT and the sctransform paper) in terms of correcting for differences in depth, mitochondrial reads etc. For clustering, we will go with Leiden because of some of the guarantees it provides in contrast to Louvain (see: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-019-41695-z). And we will use all genes.
